<subsection xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"><title> Separable Form </title>

	<introduction>

		<p>
			The method of separation of variables works by isolating the dependent and independent variables on opposite sides of the equation in a specific way, which we define below.
		</p>

		<definition xml:id="separable">
			<statement>
				A first-order differential equation is <term>separable</term> if it can be written in the <term>separable form</term>:
				<men xml:id="separable-form">
					y' = f(x) \cdot g(y) \qquad \text{or} \qquad 
					\us{\text{variables}}{\ub{\frac{1}{g(y)} \cdot y'}_{\text{dependent}}} = 
					\us{\text{variables}}{\ub{\vphantom{\frac{1}{()}}\ \ f(x)\ \ \vphantom{\frac{1}{()}}}_{\text{independent}}}
				</men>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			Writing a differential equation in separable form is the first key step in applying the separation of variables method and will be the focus of this section.
		</p>

		<note>
			<p>
				Be aware that it is not enough to put the dependent and independent variables on opposite sides of the equation. Separable form requires that <m>\frac{1}{g(y)}</m> be multiplied by the derivative term. Thus, we recommend writing the equation in the first form to avoid this oversight.
			</p>
		</note>

	</introduction>
	
	<subsubsection><title> Identifying the Separable Form </title>
		
		<p>
			The notation <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(y)</m> in the definition simply refer to any generic expression that contains only the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> variables, respectively.
		</p>

		<p>
			Examples of separable differential equations include:
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = \ob{	(x^2 + 1)	}^{f(x)} \cdot \ub{	(y - 6)^3	}_{g(y)}\ , \qquad 
				\frac{dy}{dx} = \ob{	\sin(y)		}^{g(y)} \cdot \ub{	\cos(x)		}_{f(x)}.
			</me>
			Non-separable equations include:
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = \ub{	-6x + 2y				}_{\text{not } f(x)\ \cdot\ g(y)}, \quad 
				\frac{dy}{dx} = \ub{	(x + y)(y - 6)^3	}_{\text{not } f(x)\ \cdot\ g(y)}, \quad 
				\frac{dy}{dx} = \ub{	\cos(x - y)			}_{\text{not } f(x)\ \cdot\ g(y)}.
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			A differential equation can still be separable even if one or both variables do not explicitly appear. For example:
			<me> 
				\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2
			</me>
			can be written as
			<me> 
				\frac{dy}{dx} = (\underset{f(x)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} 1 }}) \cdot 
				(\underset{g(y)}{\underset{\uparrow}{ \vphantom{|} y^2 }})
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Similarly, these equations are also separable:
			<me>
				\frac{dy}{dx} = 6x + 5, \qquad \frac{dy}{dx} = (y - 6)^3, \qquad \frac{dy}{dx} = 15.
			</me>
		</p>

		<p>
			Identifying the separable form is key to effectively applying the method of separation of variables. As you will see in the next section, recognizing this structure unlocks a nice path to solving the equation.
		</p>

		<assemblage>		
			<p>
				<xi:include href="./chkpts-1-1-separable-form-identifying-forms.ptx" />
			</p>
		</assemblage>
		
	</subsubsection>

	<subsubsection><title> Showing Separability </title>

		<p>
			Differential equations are not always presented in <xref ref="separable-form" text="custom">separable form</xref>. Verifying separability is a critical step before using the separation of variables method.
		</p>

		<p>
			Consider the following examples to practice identifying and converting equations into separable form.
		</p>
		
		<example xml:id="example-verify-separable-1">
		
			<statement>
				<p>
					Show that the differential equations are separable.
					<me> 
						\frac{dy}{dx} = x + xy^2, \qquad 
						\frac{dP}{dt} = \frac{Pt}{P^2 + 1}, \qquad 
						\frac{dy}{dx} = 11e^{4x + 3y} 
					</me>.
				</p>
			</statement>
			
			<solution><title> <term>Take out a Common Factor</term> </title>
				<p>
					Since <m>x</m> is common in both terms of the sum, we can factor it out as
					<me>
						\frac{dy}{dx} = \underset{not\ separated}{\underbrace{x + xy^2}}
						\quad \overset{algebra}{\longrightarrow} \quad 
						\frac{dy}{dx} = \underset{separated}{\underbrace{
							{\color{blue} x } ({\color{green} 1 + y^2 })
						}}
					</me>
					showing that the differential equation is <em>separable</em>.
				</p>
			</solution>

			<solution><title> <term>Product of Fractions</term> </title>
				<p>
					This example uses the following rule for multiplying fractions:
					<me>
						\frac{A\cdot B}{C\cdot D} = \frac{A}{C} \cdot \frac{B}{D}.
					</me>
					First, we split <m>P</m> and <m>t</m> in the numerator and denominator, then use the rule above to separate the fraction, like so
					<me>
						\frac{dP}{dt}
						= \underset{not\ separated}{\underbrace{\frac{Pt}{P^2 + 1}}} 
						= \frac{P\cdot t}{(P^2 + 1) \cdot (1) }
						= \underset{separated}{\underbrace{
							{\color{blue} \frac{P}{P^2 + 1} } \left({\color{green} \frac{t}{1} }\right)
						}}
					</me>
					and the equation is <em>separable</em>.
				</p>
			</solution>
			
			<solution><title> <term>Exponent Property</term> </title>
				<p>
					Applying the rule
					<me>
						e^{A + B} = e^{A} \cdot e^{B}
					</me>
					to this differential equation allows us to show it is separable as follows:
					
					<me>
						\frac{dy}{dx}
						= \underset{not\ separated}{\underbrace{11e^{4x + 3y}}} 
						= 11(e^{4x} \cdot e^{3y})
						= \underset{separated}{\underbrace{
							{\color{blue} 11e^{4x} } \cdot {\color{green} e^{3y} }
						}}.
					</me>
				</p>
			</solution>
		
		</example>

		<p>
			In some cases, the derivative term needs to be isolated first. Consider:
		</p>

		<example xml:id="example-show-separability-1">
		
			<statement>
				<p>
					Show the differential equation is separable by isolating the derivative:
					<me> x\frac{dy}{dx} + 10x^2y = 6x^2. </me>
				</p>
			</statement>
			
			<solution>

				<p>
					Let's isolate <m>dy/dx</m> on the left side of the equation, like so
					<me>  x\frac{dy}{dx} = 6x^2 - 10x^2y</me>
					<me> \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{1}{x}\left(6x^2 - 10x^2y\right) </me>
					<me> \frac{dy}{dx} = 6x - 10xy. </me>
					Now that the derivative is isolated on the left, we attempt to separate the variables on the right. Factoring <m>2x</m> out of both terms gives
					<me> \frac{dy}{dx} = 2x \cdot \left( 3 - 5y \right) </me>
					and we see that the differential equation <em>is separable</em>.
				</p>
				
				<p>
					In general, there is more than one way to separate a differential equation. This example could have been separated in either of the following ways:
					<me>\frac{dy}{dx} = x \cdot ( 6 - 10y ), \qquad \frac{dy}{dx} = ( -2x )\cdot ( 5y - 3 ) </me>
					The only thing that matters is that <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are separated.
				</p>

			</solution>
		
		</example>

		<assemblage>
			<p>
				<xi:include href="./chkpts-1-2-separable-form-showing-forms.ptx" />
			</p>
		</assemblage>
		
	</subsubsection>

</subsection>